{{Infobox person | name = Shihab al-Din al-Nuwayri | native_name = أحمد بن عبد الوهاب النويري | birth_date = April 5, 1279 | birth_place = [[Akhmim]], [[Egypt]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1333|06|05|1279|04|05}} | death_place = [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] }}
'''Al-Nuwayrī''', full name '''Shihāb al-Dīn Ahmad bin 'Abd al-Wahhāb al-Nuwayri''' ({{lang-ar|شهاب الدين أحمد بن عبد الوهاب النويري}}, born April 5, 1279 in [[Akhmim]], present-day Egypt<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Ultimate Ambition in the Arts of Erudition|last=Al-Nuwayri|first=Shihab Al-Din|publisher=Penguin Books|year=2016|isbn=978-0-14-310748-4|location=|pages=XV|via=}}</ref> – died 1333) was an Egyptian [[Muslim]] historian and civil servant of the [[Bahri Mamluk]] dynasty. He is most notable for his compilation of a 9,000-page encyclopedia of the [[Mamluk]] era, titled ''The Ultimate Ambition in the Arts of Erudition'' ({{lang|ar|نهاية الأرب في فنون الأدب}}, ''{{transl|ar|Nihayat al-arab fī funūn al-adab}}''), which pertained to [[zoology]], [[anatomy]], [[history]], [[chronology]], amongst others.<ref name=Collison>{{cite web|last1=Collison|first1=Robert L.|title=The Arab World|url=https://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/186603/encyclopaedia/32036/Japan#ref307726|website=Encyclopædia Britannica|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> He is also known for his extensive work regarding the [[Mongols]]' [[Mongol invasions of the Levant|conquest of Syria]]. Al-Nuwayri started his encyclopedia around the year 1314 and completed it in 1333.<ref name=Armstrong>{{cite web|last1=Armstrong|first1=Lyall|title=The Making of a Sufi: al-Nuwayri's Account of the Origin of Genghis Khan|url=http://mamluk.uchicago.edu/MSR_X-2_2006-Armstrong.pdf|website=Middle East Documentation Center|publisher=University of Chicago|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref>
==Life== The name Al-Nuwayri is a [[Nisba (onomastics)|nisba]] referring to the village of [[al-Nuwayra]] in present-day [[Beni Suef Governorate]]. Al-Nuwayri studied at [[Al-Azhar University]] in [[Cairo]], where he specialized in the study of the [[hadith]] and the [[Prophetic biography|sira]], in addition to history. Skilled in [[Arabic calligraphy|calligraphy]], he reportedly made a copy of ''[[Sahih al-Bukhari]]'' which he sold for 1000 [[dinar]]s. He worked as a civil servant in the administration of [[An-Nasir Muhammad]], and was in contact with the army of [[Tripoli]].
==Encyclopedia== Al-Nuwayri's encyclopedia, ''The Ultimate Ambition in the Arts of Erudition'', covered five subjects: * Geography and astronomy * Man, and what relates to him * Animals * Plants * History
The first four subjects comprised 10 volumes, while the last filled 21 volumes.
