[[File:Hendre'r_Ywydd_Uchaf_farmhouse,_St_Fagans.jpg|thumb|Hendre'r Ywydd Uchaf farmhouse]] '''Hendre'r Ywydd Uchaf''' is an early 16th-century [[cruck house]], originally constructed near [[Llangynhafal]], [[Denbighshire]], and now located at [[St Fagans National History Museum]] in [[Cardiff]], Wales. One of the interior wooden beams has been dated to the year 1508, using [[dendrochronology]].<ref>[http://www.cpat.org.uk/projects/longer/histland/clwyd/1043.htm Clwyd-Powys Archaeological Trust]. Accessed 6 June 2014</ref> The house has five bays, two of which would have been used for livestock, and an open [[hearth]]. It was designated a [[Grade II listed building]] on 10 June 1977.<ref>[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-13852-hendre-r-ywydd-uchaf-farmhouse-st-fagans/osmap British Listed Buildings]. Accessed 6 June 2014</ref>
The walls of the house are timber-framed with [[oak]] stakes bound together by a [[wattle-and-daub]] construction. The roof is [[thatch]]ed with wheat straw. There is an earth floor and unglazed windows.<ref>[http://www.coflein.gov.uk/en/site/27306/details/HENDRE%27R-YWYDD+UCHAF,+LLANGYNHAFAL/ Coflein – Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales]. Accessed 7 June 2015</ref>
The house was moved to St Fagans in 1956 and opened to the public in 1962, becoming the seventh building to be reconstructed on the site.<ref>[http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/stfagans/buildings/hendrerywydd/ National Museum of Wales – Historic buildings]. Accessed 6 June 2014</ref>
